\cf2 \cb3 Before we go to the familiarity between React and SolidJS let\'92s look at something that\'92s very important, wish is TypeScript integration.\cb1 \
\cb3 Solid was written in TypeScript and designed to provide a great developer experience with full type safety.\cb1 \
\cb3 The framework\'92s APIs are fully typed, and the compiler provides helpful error messages when you make mistakes. This not only leads to fewer runtime errors but it leads to a better code quality overall.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs60 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 Familiar yet different\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs40 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 Solid feels familiar to React developers \'97 it uses JSX, props, and a component-based architecture. But its approach to state management and rendering is fundamentally different and more efficient.\cb1 \
\cb3 Here\'92s a simple example:\cb1 \
\cb3 In React:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs32 \AppleTypeServices \cf11 \cb12 function Counter() \{\
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\
\
  return (\
    <div>\
      <p>Count: \{count\}</p>\
      <button onClick=\{() => setCount(count + 1)\}>Increment</button>\
    </div>\
  );\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf3 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 In SolidJS:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs32 \AppleTypeServices \cf11 \cb12 function Counter() \{\
  const [count, setCount] = createSignal(0);\
\
  return (\
    <div>\
      <p>Count: \{count()\}</p>\
      <button onClick=\{() => setCount(count() + 1)\}>Increment</button>\
    </div>\
  );\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf3 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 The syntax is similar, but the behavior is fundamentally different. The React component re-renders completely on every state change, while the Solid component only updates the text content inside the paragraph.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Every frontend framework is largely valued for how well it optimizes state management\cb1 \
\cb3 Signals, stores, and effects form the core of Solid\'92s state management system. Unlike React\'92s useState and useEffect hooks, these primitives are designed around true reactivity.\cb1 \
\cb3 Signals are the basic unit of state, similar to RxJS observables but optimized for UI rendering. They can be accessed and modified directly without complex state management libraries.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs32 \AppleTypeServices \cf11 \cb12 const [count, setCount] = createSignal(0);\
const doubledCount = () => count() * 2;\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf3 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 The doubledCount derivation automatically updates whenever count changes, without explicit subscriptions or dependency arrays.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 A frontend framework\'92s true power also lies in how efficiently it handles data fetching and asynchronous operations.\cb1 \
\cb3 As for Solid the resource system provides an elegant solution for data fetching and asynchronous operations. It integrates cleanly with Solid\'92s reactivity system and simplifies handling loading states.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs32 \AppleTypeServices \cf11 \cb12 const [data] = createResource(fetchData);\
return (\
  <div>\
    \{data.loading && <p>Loading...</p>\}\
    \{data.error && <p>Error: \{data.error.message\}</p>\}\
    \{data() && <DataDisplay data=\{data()\} />\}\
  </div>\
);\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf3 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 This approach eliminates the need for complex state management just to handle loading and error states, a common pain point in React applications.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs60 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 How about Server-Side rendering?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs40 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb3 SSR support is robust in Solid. Unlike some frameworks where server-side rendering feels bolted on, Solid was designed with it in mind from the beginning. The Solid Start meta-framework provides a solid foundation for SSR applications.\cb1 \
\cb3 What makes Solid\'92s SSR particularly powerful is how it integrates with its reactivity system. The same reactive primitives that make client-side code efficient also enable intelligent hydration on the client.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

